snippet.textDisplay: The problem with Cats is....It's never been the strongest Andrew Lloyd Webber musical. The reason it was such a big hit was....The stage show was strange and different and....Just an EXPERIENCE. This musical is probably a love letter to actors and actresses. It gives them a chance to really embrace musical theater and interact with the audience. I'm sure seeing the musical in a theater is quite a powerful. But....That doesn't translate well to a static screen. I'm almost willing to believe this is going to end up being one of those midnight movies like Rocky Horror where people will interact with it in a jokey manner. Eventually. But as a film....If this had come out 20 years ago....It would probably have made it's money back. But in this day and age after the musical has been out forever....Anyone that has wanted to see it probably saw it on stage long ago. Or the video that came out. Some will be angry that I say that Cats is Webber's weakest musical (or at least in the bottom). But it really has no strong story. It IS repetitive. You don't get to catch your breath...And not in a good way. With Phantom of the Opera, Jesus Christ Superstar, Evita, heck, even Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat....You can make out the story for the most part....Or at least make one in your head....From just listening to the music and words. But with Cats....It's just a hodgepodge. You know there is freaky stuff going on, but....That's about it. It's why Memory and Magical Mr. Mistopholes are the only songs that anyone really remembers with any fondness. The rest is literally just people saying Jellicle Cat over and over! And Mungojerrie and Rumpleteaser. I hate it when that song gets stuck in my head! Overall....Just not Webber's best. For a good film based on his work, check out the 1973 film version of Jesus Christ Superstar. Or even Evita with Madonna! It was actually a good movie! This one's downfall certainly wasn't it's cast....You would be surprised how many Hollywood actors did musical theater or worked in music as well. It's just....Not a great musical out of it's element and not of this time.
